 there is a natural synergy between them and labour movements committed to protecting rights of workers from commercial exploitation. Trade unions etc.In both cases it is collective action for collective benefit.\nThen along come post-modernist theories of the identity of the individual where the ills of the world were blamed on social dynamics, (I have studied post-modernism formally). The focus shifted to became about the personal experience of the individual.Don't get me wrong. These theories have done a huge amount to remove discrimination based on identity. And we are the better for it.\nBut, a couple decades ago it went tribal and morfed into a new type of class war built around the tropes of theoretical models. And more recently, like all class warfare, it has been about the exercise of, and disputation of - power. Power between self identifying identityists and those they blame for the ills of society. By the very nature of its focus of the impact on the individual, it has splintered into more and more narrowly defined identities.\nNeoliberalism focuses on the individual. It claims that in maximising the opportunities of the individual, society gains overall. Identityism makes the same claim. That in maximising the rights of the individual, society gains overall. Despite being at loggerheads, identityists and conservatives are both pursuing the cause of the rights of the individual.Neither are fighting for the collective rights of society. Both are battling for the power of groups within society.Both claim personal freedom is paramount above collective social laws where those laws inhibit the behaviour of individuals.\nNow you don't have to be Albert Einstein to see how the aims of the identity movement can and do conflict with the collective aims of the environmental movement which seeks overarching principles and laws for the protection of the environment that inevitably limit the freedom of the individual. (Such as restricted access or commercial activity.)\nEnvironmentalism seeks to limit the power of exploiters of nature.The collective good.Identityism seeks to limit the power of exploiters of minorities.The individual good.So it is not unexpected that they both end up on the left.\nBut, it is an uneasy alliance because of a fundamental dichotomy of purpose.\nWe are witnessing The Australian Greens Party ripping itself apart.And I believe that fundamental dichotomy of purpose is at the heart of its problems.\nOK. I don't mind a debate. Its a very emotional issue. But anyone wishing to dispute my analysis please refrain from personalities if you can.Cheers.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124224273", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the environmental movement grew world wide from movements that sprang up to protect landscape", "effect": "what you say is"}, {"cause": "a fundamental dichotomy of purpose", "effect": "but it is an uneasy alliance"}]}, {"id": "124230289", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1546432958000}, "author": "DavidJHursty", "author_id": "13322073", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Um, the other tricky bit for \"recycling\" is trying to separate what they get from the bins. Most people don't care much - do not read 'labelling' - some plastics cannot be 'recycled'. One thing to note is that the \"lids\" on PET plastic bottles are different.Always take the 'screw tops\" as well as the bit left behind OFF PET bottles.You will never really understand the cost of trying to separate these different plastics at the depot.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "124225065", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124230241", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1546432878000}, "author": "mountainrunnermum", "author_id": "13049145", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nEconomics, What's the cost if we do nothing to slowdown Climate Change?\nBQEND\nJust looking at the IPCC SR1.5:\n\u201cBalancing of the costs and benefits of mitigation is challenging because estimating the value of climate change damages depends on multiple parameters whose appropriate values have been debated for decades (for example, the appropriate value of the discount rate) or that are very difficult to quantify (for example,the value of non-market impacts; the economic effects of losses in ecosystem services; and the potential for adaptation, which is dependent on the rate and timing of climate change and on the socioeconomic content).\u201d\nThe best estimate of cumulative discounted damages due to 1.5C of warming by 2100 amounts to $54tn, the report says, rising to $69tn for 2C.\nhttps://www.carbonbrief.org/in-depth-qa-ipccs-special-report-on-climate-change-at-one-point-five-c\nAnd from the Stern Review, 2006:\nUsing the results from formal economic models, the Review estimates that if we don\u2019t act, the overall costs and risks of climate change will be equivalent to losing at least 5% of global GDP each year, now and forever. If a wider range of risks and impacts is taken into account, the estimates of damage could rise to 20% of GDP or more. In contrast, the costs of action \u2013 reducing greenhouse gas emissions to avoid the worst impacts of climate change \u2013 can be limited to around 1% of global GDP each year. \nhttps://grist.files.wordpress.com/2006/11/summary_of_conclusions.pdf", "recommendation_count": "16", "in_reply_to": "124229143", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "estimating the value of climate change damages depends on multiple parameters whose appropriate values have been debated for decades value that are very difficult to quantify", "effect": "balancing of the costs and benefits of mitigation is challenging"}, {"cause": "1.5c of warming", "effect": "the best estimate of cumulative discounted damages"}]}, {"id": "124230011", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1546432480000}, "author": "David Jones", "author_id": "17095222", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "While on the one hand it's true that we need solid policie