pital. In a barely-efficient world the only limit to production is availability of working citizens. Unemployment is not only unjust, it is also inefficient and completely unnecessary, not a natural human state at all.\nSo where did capitalism come from and why has it destroyed the Earth?\nWhen the above creed was first written down by an unknown journalist in 1879 in then-remote San Francisco, Henry George, in the legendary Progress and Poverty. He sparked a global movement, including catalysing formation of Australian Labour. George was opposed to Marx's uncompromising revolution, preferring a social evolutionary approach, combining the best of individualism and collectivism based on the natural economy of the Earth and human desire/need.\nWhile Marx was left to rearrange his manuscripts and even foment revolution on the outskirts of Europe, Henry George's thesis of a single tax on commercial land value to singularly fund civilisation gravely threatened established global power elites.\nGeorge had set out to discover the true cause of recessions, and why the worst poverty always seemed to accompany the most progress. Succeeding spectacularly, Progress and Poverty promised salvation in this life, not the next, and remains the only published work in history to outsell the Bible, globally, in a single year. Which it did for twenty consecutive years.\nFrom Progress and Poverty chapter 17: \"The Problem Explained\":\nBQSTART\nThree things unite in production: land, labor, and capital. Three parties divide the output: landowner, laborer, and capitalist. If the laborer and capitalist get no more as production increases, it is a necessary inference that the landowner takes the gain. \nThe facts agree with this inference. Neither wages nor interest keep step with material progress. Yet rising rents and land values invariably accompany advancement. Indeed, they are the mark of progress! Increasing rent explains why wages and interest do not increase. The same cause that gives more to the land owner also denies it to the laborer and capitalist. \n..In short, the value of land depends entirely on the power that ownership gives to appropriate the wealth created by labor. Land value always increases at the expense of labor. The reason greater productive power does not increase wages is because it increases the value of land. Rent swallows up the whole gain.\n That is why poverty accompanies progress.\nBQEND\nSo he was stopped. Since they could not refute his arguments, Land Barons, Industrialists and Bankers literally bought entire economics departments to corrupt the language to steal the very value of civilisation itself; Oil magnate John. D. Rockefeller created the Chicago school of Poison, Railroad Tycoon Ely Stanford started Stanford university, Banker J.P. Morgan founded Columbia.\nIn the process of so doing, they emasculated the discipline of economics, stripped dignity from labour and set in motion a planet-wrecking doctrine. Neo-Classical economics aka neoliberalism aka capitalism was born, for the benefit of rent-takers and to the catastrophic detriment of the working-citizen and the living world upon which s/he depends.\nReferences:", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it increases the value of land", "effect": "the reason greater productive power does not increase wages is"}]}, {"id": "124224859", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1546422494000}, "author": "hhmmm", "author_id": "2770693", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I've been vegetarian since 1979 and haven't flown since 1984.....and look how well things are turning out!", "recommendation_count": "2", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124224707", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1546422176000}, "author": "FallenApple", "author_id": "100522246", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\u201cIt is liberalism\u2019s most dangerous lie that an individual\u2019s action can solve problems of this scale.\u201d\nNever knock the lit