0000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The changes in ocean chemistry are some the more disturbing changes we\u2019re seeing.\nThe surface waters of the ocean are warmer and less dense than waters at depth, so it takes a lot of energy to turn the ocean over. As the surface now warms faster than the depths, it gets harder to turn the ocean over, so the ocean becomes more strongly stratified.\nNutrient rich waters from the depths slow their journey to the surface where they feed important fisheries like sardines and anchoveta and oxygen rich waters from the surface slow their journey to the depths, turning the ocean to desert.\nThere\u2019s a notable blue blob in the N Atlantic, just south of Greenland which some scientists suggest indicates a possible slowdown of the AMOC, or Atlantic overturning circulation, part of which carries tropical heat towards Europe.\nThere may also be some effect on that current from increased freshwater input from Greenland\u2019s ice sheet. And in the Southern Hemisphere Antarctic bottom water formation is slowing, perhaps due to a similar process with that ice sheet's meltwater.", "recommendation_count": "11", "in_reply_to": "124756185", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "a similar process with that ice sheet 's meltwater", "effect": "and in the southern hemisphere antarctic bottom water formation is slowing"}]}, {"id": "124756825", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547690320000}, "author": "ID6902426", "author_id": "1456771", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "As you were already asked, any examples?", "recommendation_count": "11", "in_reply_to": "124756445", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124756729", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547689641000}, "author": "SFromNl", "author_id": "17048054", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nSubmarines use them for concealment as they reflect sound and sonar.\nBQEND\nWow that's cool. 