l for the adults. Bites were frequent, painful and itchy for days. \nBut all those years ago the boys had got it wrong \u2013 it is only the females that bite and suck your blood to provide the nourishment for the eggs they are about to lay. The males lack the sharp mouthparts to cut through your skin and are harmless nectar eaters and beneficial pollinators. \nIt is too early to say whether last year\u2019s unwelcome population surge will be repeated; the larvae do not emerge as adults until May. ", "keyword_urls": ["https://www.theguardian.com/environment/insects", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-change", "https://www.theguardian.com/tone/features"], "share_count": "0", "description": "Last summer\u2019s heatwave resulted in an unwelcome rise in the number of Haematopota pluvialis", "date_published": {"$date": 1548192630000}, "date_modified": {"$date": 1548192630000}, "authors": ["Paul Brown"], "article_section": "Environment", "article_tags": ["Environment", "Insects", "Climate change", "UK news"], "og_fields": {"og:url": "http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/jan/22/specieswatch-will-population-of-nasty-cleg-fly-surge-again", "og:description": "Last summer\u2019s heatwave resulted in an unwelcome rise in the number of Haematopota pluvialis", "og:image": "https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/61b7be1db7394828a8012edf86e5a32363659b6b/0_6_3584_2152/master/3584.jpg?width=1200&height=630&quality=85&auto=format&fit=crop&overlay-align=bottom%2Cleft&overlay-width=100p&overlay-base64=L2ltZy9zdGF0aWMvb3ZlcmxheXMvdGctZGVmYXVsdC5wbmc&s=f5d5d6585874a66dc4211c19e7dfec31", "og:type": "article", "og:title": "Specieswatch: will population of nasty Cleg fly surge again?"}, "discussion_section_open": false, "headline": "l", "article_image": [{"type": "http://schema.org/ImageObject", "properties": {"representativeOfPage": "true", "url": "https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/61b7be1db7394828a8012edf86e5a32363659b6b/0_6_3584_2152/master/3584.jpg?width=700&quality=85&auto=fo