e Great Fire) acted more like a dam on the river than the ones that replaced it in their turn.", "recommendation_count": "7", "in_reply_to": "125129878", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the high tides could not spread into the neighbouring streets and fields", "effect": "This led to greater movement because the high tides could not spread into the neighbouring streets and fields ."}]}, {"id": "125135107", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548584546000}, "author": "xiphoid", "author_id": "100526028", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Yes I am and that was the case. Since then the Thames has been significantly narrowed but simultaneously dredged deeper hence reducing surface area available to lose heat. The other posters you refer to clearly have not understood the issues of flow and velocity.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125129878", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125129878", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548564955000}, "author": "Klapper", "author_id": "3638543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "That would be true if you are basing your argument on the greater surface area exposure of the flowing water (greater heat transfer to the air).", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125124739", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125129844", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548564608000}, "author": "Klapper", "author_id": "3638543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Like some other posters here you're confusing velocity with flow volume. The beaver dam freezes by slowing velocity via a large increase in cross-sectional area. Flow does not change all other things being equal. \nRocky and Gpwayne I think are both making this mistake. In fact dredging will slow velocity since cross-section is increased (watershed, groundwater flux and precipitation staying the same of course).", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125123381", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125129744", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548563800000}, "author": "Klapper", "author_id": "3638543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The flow rate upstream of a dam will not be reduced by the dam. That is a determined by watershed size and precipitation, groundwater flux etc. The Thames is no different. Restrictions to flow will not reduce volume. One of 2 things will happen at a restriction. The velocity will increase or the cross sectional area of the flow will increase to negate the constriction. The latter is is known as a \"flood\".\nIn any case the key point is flow rate will not be reduced (or increased) by changing constriction. That can obviously happen for other reasons like seasonal fluctuations or drought but not because of bridge construction or dredging.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125122058", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "bridge construction or dredging", "effect": "not"}]}, {"id": "125128191", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548554321000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Not only do we have less river ice, we have less lake ice, less seasonal snow cover, less seasonally frozen ground, less perennially frozen ground, we have smaller glaciers, we have shrinking ice sheets, we have loss of sea ice. \nAll the big pieces of snow and ice which care about temperature most are shrinking.", "recommendation_count": "7", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125128146", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548554080000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "In addition to the lack of comments on climate articles I think that the Guardian could place these articles more prominently.\nIt would also be good if comments were left open longer. Sometimes articles have appeared after I went to bed and comments closed before I woke up.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "125121920", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "