 much higher occurrence rate than we experience today, but it is not an ice age \u2013 little or otherwise.\nBQEND\nThe Medieval Warm Period and the Little Ice Age were concepts introduced about 50 years ago by early climate researchers, particularly Hubert Lamb, based on evidence available at that time, but the more they are investigated the more ephemeral they become.\nTrue ice ages involve snow remaining throughout summers across large areas, which didn't happen during the so-called Little Ice Age.\nGlacial inception requires summer temperatures in the northern hemisphere to be low enough for snow to build up year on year, starting mainly on north-facing slopes of mountain ranges.", "recommendation_count": "17", "in_reply_to": "125098217", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125103278", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548483696000}, "author": "rockyrex", "author_id": "2923581", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The final nail in the coffin for frost fairs was the replacement of London Bridge in the 1830s.\nThe old bridge had lots of narrow arches and caused slow water flow - the replacement had a few wide arches.", "recommendation_count": "24", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the old bridge", "effect": "slow water flow"}]}, {"id": "125100974", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548468162000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "My cousins in Denmark mentioned to me that they used to enjoy skating in the wintertime but that lately it's been too warm and the winters there are just dreary.", "recommendation_count": "8", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125100118", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548464507000}, "author": "JohnFallhammer", "author_id": "1345293", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The little ice age was a regional phenomenon. That's the main reason it's not relevant to considerations of global warming.\nI think what you're saying is probably reasonable bu