omy flight isn't seen as a luxury, but is hugely costly in carbon terms. Aviation is an interesting example: 11 billion gallons of jet fuel were consumed by US airlines last year, but private and corporate jets registered in the US consumed just 1 million gallons. Now of course per person private flying is hugely more costly in carbon terms, but it accounts for one ten thousandth of fuel consumed, so it really makes no difference - the planet doesn't care about 1 million, it cares about 11 billion.\nSo, irrespective of what 'the rich' do, however you define them, we should all make a difference. If we say the rich have to set an example before we'll act, we're basically saying we're allowing ourselves to be controlled by the actions of an elite group that we have to follow and we can't think for ourselves. And lots of 'the rich' may be reining in their carbon footprints, but are we saying that so long as we see a few (say 1,500 out of a population of 8 billion) flying private jets that we should carry on driving our 3 litre 2 ton cars to the shops instead of riding a bike?", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "125215265", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125220184", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548766792000}, "author": "OverHillAndDale", "author_id": "16484359", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "What an elaborate evasion tactic!\nYou trivial little thing. You made a completely unfounded claim (that we can all adapt to anything climate change throws at us), and then demand that anyone else prove you are wrong. That's the real evasion tactic.\nBQSTART\nUnless you or Matthew 2012 can point to a single one of the above hypothetical impacts that we cannot adapt to, then your claims are clearly tosh. \nBQEND\nI did. You tell me how people are supposed to 'adapt' to an increase in famine and starvation. Set up a hedge fund?", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125183359", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125203299", "time_stamp": {