221", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The World Bank, IMF, OECD and other authorities are predicting a massive hit to the global economy. NATO and the Pentagon are among those expecting mass migration and social unrest. While a few areas may benefit, agriculture will be severely impacted in many parts of the world.There are still of course major uncertainties in our modelling of future climate - mainly around the various 'tipping-points' which by their nature are hard to predict. Overall however it appears that we are on a trajectory towards at least 3 degrees C rise in global mean temperatures. If corporations think they will be able to cash in by selling more fans, aircon units, generators or hand-crank phone chargers, that might work in the very short-term; but in terms of decadal trends they are probably dreaming. An economic crash and social unrest are not conducive to a retail boom - except perhaps in firearms.\nhttp://www.worldbank.org/en/news/feature/2015/11/08/rapid-climate-informed-development-needed-to-keep-climate-change-from-pushing-more-than-100-million-people-into-poverty-by-2030\nhttps://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2008/01/pdf/c4.pdf\nhttps://www.ft.com/content/0ba2390a-ffd4-11e8-ac00-57a2a826423e\nhttps://news.nationalgeographic.com/2017/09/climate-change-costs-us-economy-billions-report/\nhttps://phys.org/news/2018-07-sea-world-trillion-year.html\nhttp://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736%2815%2901156-3/abstract\nhttp://www.newsweek.com/pentagon-report-us-military-considers-climate-change-immediate-threat-could-277155\nhttps://phys.org/news/2018-05-climate-variability-world-poorest-countries.html#nRlv\nhttp://thebulletin.org/nato-joins-pentagon-deeming-climate-change-threat-multiplier10790\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/mar/19/climate-change-soon-to-cause-mass-movement-world-bank-warns", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "125191140", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "12518