 is a way of assuring that future generations that benefit from such goods pay their part. The incentives to build for future generations of users in commercial or residential building need to be addressed to spread the costs over time. When carrying out net present value estimations for such investments the question of what discount rate to use and how these should vary over time needs much more work: a start was provided by Giglio et al [\"VERY LONG-RUN DISCOUNT RATES\" https://www.nber.org/papers/w20133.pdf]. Of course one way to go is to impose stricter building envelope energy standards at least for new buildings - for retrofitting existing buildings that would be a hot potato given that even suggesting an acceleration to renewable carbon-free power is politically difficult.", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125405431", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1549127108000}, "author": "onthefence", "author_id": "2490315", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nWalsunda - It is not the question because to significantly decrease CO2 emissions large amounts of storage are not needed (particularly in countries with large gas reserves)\nBQEND\nWell, quite. A renewables grid locks in gas.\nA wind+solar+gas calculation based on UK wind statistics (e.g. Table 6 here) shows that if you have enough gas capacity to meet 100% of UK consumption over a year, then \u2014 even with additional solar \u2014 20% of generation ends up being gas as backup for wind lulls. That gives you an aggregate carbon intensity of 113g CO\u2082/kWh for the electricity system as a whole.\nThe UK emissions target is 50g CO\u2082/kWh. \nUsing gas as backup for wind lulls won't decarbonise electricity. That's a well-known and uncontentious point. The odd thing about your position is that you don't seem to dispute the numbers, you simply don't have a problem with that state of affairs.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125402315", "causal_relat