 review of the total number of papers only 33.6% actually directly expressed an opinion about causality and of those 97% endorsed AGW.\nThe second follow up paper directly addresses the problem of taking a paper that expresses no position on causes as being negative or non-committal as in itself being a flawed view and explains why that is so.\nYou seem to have a POV which I don't think any amount of evidence is going to change. I do not doubt your sincerity, nor your apparent intelligence, but I think you don't seem to understand how scientific consensus is developed nor do you seem to understand the nature of the meta-analysis presented in these papers.\nI wasn't going to respond as it did not seem worthwhile, but I just did not want to let your last analysis go unanswered lest someone else only read the abstract and was misled by the conclusions you seem to draw.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125395899", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125385439", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1549049426000}, "author": "Mazter", "author_id": "11150889", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nDon't expect renewables to be reliable or cheap, in the medium term at least.\nBQENDCorrect. They are already cheap now, will be even cheaper in the short term future, and very cheap in the medium term (not just cheap).\nBTW, already reliable, and even if you do lose a wind turbine or PV panel, or even a string, they rest of the farm will keep going as they are modular, and so will all the other farms. Whereas with large FF and nuclear generation, you can lose 100MWh's, even a GW+ of generation in one single go, when there's a problem.", "recommendation_count": "8", "in_reply_to": "125360101", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125400547", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1549107445000}, "author": "NewmanOldjoke", "author_id": "12684952", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Those_predictions_were_made-in-advance...as is customary!I'm now do