based articles.\nFor those of us that support RE (not nuclear campaigners) we can clearly see that demand side storage, even in homes, benefits the national grids through offset, after all, if a powerstation (even a small domestic PV system) is added to 'the grid' then it's supply will impact the grid.\nIf a homeowner doesn't ask for a kW of power, or their neighbours don't need it because the 'small powerstation' is exporting next door, then the national grid doesn't get asked for that kW.\nOnce you put maths tricks, or deliberate anti-RE and anti-storage spin aside, you see that domestic storage benefits all. And the big benefit is that the CAPEX is borne by the household, not the grid for the batts.\nI note that in Aus, households with storage can join schemes that negotiate on their behalf to provide additional supply to the grids during peak periods by having 1,000's of households export from their batts. Not only do the households get paid peak prices for that leccy, but all of Aus benefits as the increased supply helps to reduce peak prices.\nI seem to recall a news article from a year or so back, where households were receiving about A$1/kWh for export because the grid price was peaking around $1,400/MWh at that time.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "125387212", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the powerstation is exporting next door", "effect": "their neighbours do n't need it"}, {"cause": "the grid price was peaking around $ 1,400/mwh at that time", "effect": "where households were receiving about a$ 1/kwh for export"}]}, {"id": "125384257", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1549045198000}, "author": "goliver4", "author_id": "3758197", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Was wondering if Australia have any Mined-out Solution Mines? I don't think there any current CAES plants, as to my knowledge only two in the World, Alabama and Germany. If you had a plant, many/most of the coal fired power stations could be retired as generation fr