 CO2 has increased. This tells us that fossil fuel [light carbon] emissions are the largest contributor of atmospheric CO2 concentrations since the pre-industrial era. Methane emission increase is also unquestionably largely anthropogenic.CO2 emission from volcanic sources are one hundredth or less of our annual output.We know it's not the sun, because we have well estimated its output, and variation, over the century. https://agwobserver.wordpress.com/2013/01/07/papers-on-the-role-of-the-sun-in-recent-global-warming/And the pattern of solar induced heating would be different: currently the stratosphere and higher is cooling, not warming as it would if extra solar output was reaching the planet. We are retarding the escape of energy from the surface by increasing atmospheric opacity to IR with anthropogenic GHGs.We know its not a dominance of El Nino over La Nina because those tendencies cancel one another out over the century.If it's not our emissions, which have the right properties, forcing/m2, quantity and persistence to match the observed temperature trend, where is an equivalent forcing coming from?It's us, Felix.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "125362602", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "our emissions", "effect": "this warming"}, {"cause": "we have well estimated its output over the century", "effect": "it 's not the sun"}, {"cause": "those tendencies cancel one another out over the century", "effect": "we know its not a dominance of el nino over la nina"}]}, {"id": "125362849", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548999186000}, "author": "reinhardpolley", "author_id": "16020012", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "As ever you only tell half the story, that's not what AEMO thinks \"based on current cost projections\"", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125361974", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125362814", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548998883000}, "author": "reinhardpolley", "author_id": "16020012", "schema_org_type": "h