"recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125325122", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125362621", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548997319000}, "author": "Vlamingo", "author_id": "15902664", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nBecause 'increasing GHGs can lead to warming' can mean lead to significant warming, or it could mean lead to insignificant warning\nBQEND\nExtra CO2 added to the atmosphere in the quantities that we are unequivocally causes significant warming. The scientific basis for this is rock solid. It creates an energy imbalance between heat coming in and that going out. The magnitude of that imbalance can be predicted by physics, and is confirmed by both direct (satellite) and indirect (total Earth heat content) measurements. It is equivalent to setting off several nuclear bombs every second of every day.\nUnless there is significant long term change in some other forcing (and there is no reason to expect any), this process must continue until the Earth warms sufficiently to radiate more heat to space than previously, eliminating the imbalance.\nAll this is settled basic science.\nMuch is of course unsettled. The Earth system is very big, the heat is not distributed equally amongst its different compartments and there are complicated feedback mechanisms. So it is difficult to know how long it will take, and what the ultimate temperature change will be at the surface where we live. \nBut there is absolutely no doubt that it is very much significant. The surface has warmed by 0.8C in less than 50 years, which by planetary standards is huge. And there is no known mechanism other than extra CO2 that can account for it.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "125361995", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "Because ' increasing GHGs can lead to warming '", "effect": "can mean lead to significant warming or it could mean lead to insignificant warning bqend extra co2 added to the atmosphere in the quantities that we are unequiv