 a question of temperature, but of humidity and prevailing air currents etc. Opening the house in cooler night periods is very likely to be be a part of addressing such issues. The key thing is that 'passive' measures will often require active management, rather than just 'set and forget'. It requires a different mindset, one more attuned to local conditions. But that shouldn't be seen as onerous, rather, as becoming conscious (just like recycling).", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "125360699", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125361659", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548988744000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Of course it is. But we can get photons for free without having fusion within 150,000,000 km.", "recommendation_count": "7", "in_reply_to": "125355191", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125360759", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548983679000}, "author": "FelixKruell", "author_id": "14432870", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Yep, that's a rolling replacement of existing plants (with renewables/storage/gas).\nAs a result, we will continue to rely on coal for decades (until that rolling replacement is complete):\nBQSTART\nYet AEMO\u2019s overall plan is still to retain existing coal-fired stations for as long as they can be economically relied on. AEMO assumes a strong role for coal up to 2030 and beyond, and forecasts that many large power stations (Vales Point, Gladstone, Yallourn, Eraring, Bayswater) will retire between 2030 and 2040.\nBQEND", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "125334523", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125360757", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548983670000}, "author": "NewmanOldjoke", "author_id": "12684952", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "They even considered building their own PS, no? But that would have belled the cat somewhat.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125360565", "causal_relati