s of the ocean. So it takes a lot of energy to turn the ocean over (takes around 1,000 years).\nNow as the surface warms faster than the depths it gets harder to turn the ocean over, so it gets more strongly stratified.\nNutrient-rich waters from the depths which feed important fisheries like the anchoveta and sardines slow their journey to the surface. And oxygen-rich surface waters slow their journey to the depths and the ocean turns to desert.\nThere's also the problem of fresh meltwater from the ice sheets which seems to have been slowing Antarctic bottom water formation and the AMOC.", "recommendation_count": "4", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124506534", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547176425000}, "author": "Nigel Evans", "author_id": "18426188", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "And who was bragging in the pub that the environmental flows went to cotton farmers so the greenies wouldn't get it.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124467242", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124506076", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547173932000}, "author": "nogapsallowed", "author_id": "4541452", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"... the amount of energy absorbed by the oceans was equivalent to an atomic bomb per second for the past 150 years.\" \nThat comparison is contained in the Guardian's analysis of the latest scientific report indicating ocean temperatures are rising at a rate far higher than previously predicted. \nBANG BANG BANG BANG ... will someone please open the doors of Australia's parliamentary bunkers so the politicians can get some inkling of the firecracker environment the world is now living in?\nIn the meantime, everyone who bought into the Gold Coast, or Sydney's Sylvania Waters, or any of the other irresponsible postwar developments built on sandbars and canalised wetlands should sell now. Venice has already seen knee deep waters in St Mark's Square and the dozens of other see level cities are not f