 over $150k+super. If these jobs were truly opened up to offers from the local community, the cost of running local government would be significantly reduced. It does not need to go back to the Ancient Greek idea where people volunteered for public work, but we should at least be calling for bids to not discourage those who might be prepared to do any given job for a lesser impost on the many retirees etc who actually pay for such public sector wages.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "124756706", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "they got to up vote", "effect": "and a dozen are on $ 150k+ packages"}]}, {"id": "124757903", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547696302000}, "author": "mcs_095", "author_id": "11861630", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "So Milto, when will you suggest that the negative externality costs are factored in with regard to coal power plants when doing comparisons? Oh that's rights, they don't count do they :P\nIf it is fair for one, its fair for all.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124756829", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124757856", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547695961000}, "author": "Djerbecca", "author_id": "12351053", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It is worth remembering that the mania for being \u2018fair\u2019 to the private sector has also raised the price of natural gas. I can remember when it was an inexpensive way to heat water, cook and heat living and work space because there was so much of it and it was totally contained in Australia. \nTHEN it became cost effective to turn it into LPG and export it. But, then the companies persuaded governments that it was unfair for Australians to pay less than the world price (for LPG) for the gas already flowing to our homes. Oh, dear the gas price went up, up, up because you know, world market, competition, etc. Or was it the greedy desire to sell more than Qatar and so treat domestic customers as free floating internation