ps Acacia melanoxylon (blackwood), Atherosperma moschatum (black sassafras), Doryphora sassafras (sassafras), Elaeocarpus holopetalus and Eucryphia moorei (pinkwood) predominate.\nRainforests occur in areas that are reliably moist, free from fire and have moderate to highly fertile soils. Comprised of a variety of broad-leaved evergreen trees, and very few eucalypts, rainforests represent relics of vegetation linked to other forests in the southern hemisphere. They contain many \u2018primitive\u2019 plants that are direct decendants of the earliest Gondwanan flowering forms.\nTree seedlings of rainforest plants are able to successfully establish in deep shade and enter a state of dormancy until a gap in the canopy is formed, usually due to the death and fall of older trees. Species compete for the new space and light in a perpetual process known as \u2018gap-phase dynamics\u2019. This is in contrast to other vegetation formations, which rely on stochastic events such as fire, flood or drought-breaking rain to drive regeneration. \nhttps://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/threatenedspeciesapp/VegClass.aspx?vegClassName=Southern+Warm+Temperate+Rainforests\nhttps://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/threatenedSpeciesApp/VegFormation.aspx?formationName=Rainforests\nTemperate rainforests are flammable after loggers have cut down most of the trees, bulldozed all the tree ferns and then set fire to the landscape, or after a long and severe drought.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125309449", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the death and fall of older trees", "effect": "enter a state of dormancy until a gap in the canopy is formed"}]}, {"id": "125359011", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548975391000}, "author": "bangor1", "author_id": "14038383", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Another thought is that your utter negativity does not include a suggestion to tow the Waddamana Power Station to a safe location, nor to remove all the fauna, wallabies, quolls, d