ngthens further the case that climate change is driving an increase in the frequency and intensity of extreme weather events, documented on every continent except Antarctica.\nIn last year\u2019s analysis, we identified 59 papers published in 2016 and 2017 exploring a possible link between climate change and amplification of extreme weather events, of which 41 found a positive signal of climate change. The additional year has brought a further 43 papers, of which 32 found a positive link from climate change to the event\u2019s likelihood or intensity. Of the new batch, only four found that climate change decreased the chances of a particular extreme event, and these all involved snow and/or cold temperatures.\" [The Seeker Jan 8. 2019]", "recommendation_count": "14", "in_reply_to": "124598860", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "the paris agreement"}]}, {"id": "124602883", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547457873000}, "author": "JonShone", "author_id": "15198700", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You may not be lazy at downloading data, but you certainly are unaware of the irony in your statement. The idea that a cif poster has got a better understanding of the situation than publishing climate scientists with peer reviewed work, scientists from nasa, the noaa and the many others who produce reports for the ipcc, is what lacks credibility.", "recommendation_count": "13", "in_reply_to": "124591524", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124602364", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547457010000}, "author": "chrisbrown", "author_id": "3684556", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Some may want to restrict themselves to a discussion of heat in a particular place in a particular month but the article is clearly about wider weather patterns. These extreme weather events are not weather as usual but seasonal weather plus the intensifier of warming. To speak bluntly, climate change has acted as an amplifier turning up the vo\u00f6ume