 - and possibly worthwhile - undertaking. The most helpful thing I have read along the lines (I think) of what you are suggesting is Kate Raworth's Doughnut Economics which I think you would find in tune with at least some of your thinking, and which is a very serious look at what is wrong with current economic thinking.\nYou're right in that understanding the science is not sufficient in itself to make a difference. We have to persuade our leaders to do something about it, and with some urgency. Actually, a lot of urgency. But I would also like to think we can do this through democratic means....", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "124577300", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124584168", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547397267000}, "author": "quietreason", "author_id": "14769888", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nDoes your scientific knowledge go as far as setting up millions of profitable people-centred, environmentally-friendly, non-material, minimum-energy-consuming jobs to replace millions of climate-changing superfluous consumer goods ones as a way to evolve the economy away from the existing alarming one?\nBQENDThe existence of any living entity tends to change the environment to some degree. As a prime example: our atmosphere once had a suffocating concentration of CO2 with almost zero oxygen but ~2.3 billion years ago underwent a massive change to oxygen-rich in the Great Oxidation Event (GOE) It appears that the GOE was triggered some 0.4 billion years earlier by the evolution of multicellular cyanobacteria - still with us today. It seems the greenhouse effect of that earlier CO2-rich atmosphere had kept the earth warm at a time when the early sun was far cooler than it is now.\nThat we exist today would still affect the atmosphere, earth and oceans even if we made nothing and lived by eating plants and occasional bare-handed sheep strangling, because any living thin consumes and emits. The GOE was a cataclysmic event at its time, but even that was a gradual process (it took 0.4bn years) compared with today's man-driven rates of CO2 and climate change.\nUntil the early C19th our effect on atmospheric CO2 was barely noticeable, swamped as it was by natural CO2-consuming processes. Even so, we were leaving various mineral footprints through our exploitation of metallurgy (lead poisoning being just one recurring issue, and having left a legible record in soil and bones since the Roman era and before, right up to today - e.g. Flint, Michigan). So a livable society without excessive CO2 emissions is possible.\nWhat is different today is our insatiable demand for \"energy\" which we most readily generate from the combustion of carbon-rich natural materials found now in fossil form as coal, oil, natural gas. Before 1800 most of our combustible fuel came from felling trees which, if re-planted, recovered the CO2 emitted by our combustion of the predecessors. Today, however, we're emitting CO2 at about twice the rate at which all available natural processes can remove it (and the significant proportion of this as oceanic absorption does not exactly \"remove\" CO2, just holds it for later emission).\nNow suppose we learn to halve, or much better than halve, our profligate CO2 emissions? That need not betoken the end of commerce, industry, travel. Indeed, we would certainly need the first 2 of these in good nick in order to achieve such a reduction, 'though far less travel of goods and people would certainly help balance the equation.\nSo let's have more local manufacture and agriculture; more truly community-based care; less conspicuous consumption; better-quality and longer-lasting products; more efficient and lighter vehicular transport. And let's bring back real work and skills for our young people, or those many for whom compulsorily extended school feels like a sentence of confinement, saving them from sterile addiction to smart-phones and social media and giving them real pride in achievement. Yet also encourage arts, literature and learning for learning's sake.\nDo that, and we really could have a worthwhile, low-carbon economy which might, just might, have the means and brains to survive the coming climatic crisis.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "124557894", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124583495", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547394947000}, "author": "chrisbrown", "author_id": "3684556", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "correction \"I think what [you] mean is . . . \"", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "124579603", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124581638", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547390396000}, "author": "werdzwerth", "author_id": "12826250", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I have been posting comments on CiF about creating a new money supply through making people-centred, environmentally-friendly jobs profitable and this is about the first time they have drawn a response but it seems that while so many know so much about climate change, we are mostly in the dark about replacing destructive work with non-destructive work, and destructive here also means the drudgery for the workforce. A good way of reducing carbon emissions is by creating millions of non-emissons jobs, enabling workers to move from the former sector into this new one, and so the destructive workplaces will disappear.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124565161", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124580719", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547388271000}, "author": "werdzwerth", "author_id": "12826250", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I like reading about amateurs and non-trained people who have shown consecrated scientists to be speaking pure fiction. Palaeontologists were very prone to making amazing theories based on virtually no evidence only to be shown up!\nI observe and analyse but my bent is unannounced quite spontaneous artistic intervention in the pub