f the existing industrial facilities and turbines as possible. Converting steel production and other industrial processes to hydrogen is relatively straightforward; conversion to electricity is actually not possible in most cases - high grade process heat is often required. \nAnd for transport; we will need a charge point for every single car sold; where the vast majority of people living in cities do not have a private garage. I have studied this extensively, and as the TUV SUD e-mobility chief explains; all these 11kW charge points will require significant upgrades to the grid. If people want more range; more energy needs to be provided; so its constantly increasing cost for laying cables and upgrading substations.\nActually, he puts the cost for Germany at about \u20ac52 billion for electric charging, and \u20ac40 billion for hydrogen refuelling stations. I'd be inclined to agree with his figures; despite electricity grid operators being quite optimistic about what can be achieved - once the percentage increases; the grid infrastructure problems appear - and just simply the fact that so many million chargers need to be installed on streets. \nThen you've got the range and recharging issues. \nSo ultimately; we have to use hydrogen for the majority of use cases where we use fossil fuels today. If batteries were a genuine panacea, then it would be obvious to use them. The problem is that the characteristics of fossil fuels; including the storing transporting and weight-to-energy value, among other things, has meant that we are going to continue using them; or something like them. And the only element that resembles fossil fuels is hydrogen. \nWe have no choice; and the more people want to keep confusing the situation by thinking that we can store infinite amounts of energy in batteries are really slowing down what needs to be achieved quickly: a wholesale shift to hydrogen in all sectors - and the absolute best way of doing this is via a decarbonised gas grid.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124560136", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124562148", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547322550000}, "author": "werdzwerth", "author_id": "12826250", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I am not a denier. It was very clear what my doubts were about.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124557869", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124562121", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547322480000}, "author": "Daniel21x", "author_id": "101241012", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "(Part a)\nFrom the UK government websitehttps://www.gov.uk/government/news/plan-to-enable-first-uk-carbon-capture-project-from-the-mid-2020s-announced-at-world-first-summit\nBQSTART\nThe overarching ambition is to roll out the technology at scale in the 2030s, subject to costs coming down sufficiently. \nThe plan commits the UK to:\n\u2022 next year set out how to enable the UK\u2019s first CCUS facility\u2022 invest \u00a320 million in supporting construction of CCUS technologies at industrial sites across the UK, as part of \u00a345 million commitment to innovation\u2022 invest up to \u00a3315 million in decarbonising industry, including the potential to use CCUS\u2022 begin work with the Oil and Gas Authority, industry and the Crown Estate and Crown Estate Scotland to identify existing oil and gas infrastructure which could be transformed for CCUS projects\nBQEND\nI know this is complicated. Trust me; I spend all my time researching and then explaining this to people; and I am aware there was a huge fuss made about hydrogen in the early 00s, and nothing came of it.\nWhats changed today is that we have very low cost renewables. In fact, we are approaching a nominal value for renewables lower than the natural gas import price; so very simplistically its cheaper. So this goes some way to explain why the world is now coming around to the idea again, after getting burned in the 00s.\nBut let me explain why there is no other option to hydrogen. First of all, the gas grid carries 5-7 times the peak capacity of the electricity grid. So when everyone turns their heating on, they use gas - and this is a large amount of energy that we cannot replace like-for-like with electricity. Initially, this is because we don't have that amount of dispatchable generation (gas turbines), and as mentioned the electricity grid can't transport that amount of electricity in one go.\nNow, the other reason we can't use electricity is because ASHP units cannot realistically replace gas boilers. ASHP essentially provides constant low-level heat; and so it requires very good insulation and very good windows. It also means that pipes and ducts need to be installed; and windows need to remain closed. It is unfair to ask the 80% of people in the UK who use gas currently, to switch to ASHP units. So thats why this is very unlikely to actually happen - the cost of insulating and installing these systems will mean that the system is simply unaffordable for most people. It will not happen; putting in 20cm insulation in an old house is both beyond the means and beyond the inclination of most homeowners.\nThe far easier answer is to replace the gas that goes through the existing gas network, with minor modification. A lot is made by certain types of people of the fact that this is difficult. It is not; and the detailed 544 page report from Northern Gas Networks should convince even the most skeptical person that they do indeed have the ability to convert the gas network to hydrogen, within budget.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124560136", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "we do n't have that amount of dispatchable generation turbines and as mentioned the electricity grid ca n't transport that amount of electricity in one go", "effect": "initially this is"}, {"cause": "ashp units can not realistically replace gas boilers", "effect": "now the other reason we ca n't use electricity is"}]}, {"id": "12