12", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "(Part b)\nNow, the other route to hydrogen is via CCS. Many extensive studies have been completed over the last few years and the government has finally agreed to an extensive CCS program in the UK, to start with large industrial users. The elegance of this route is that reformers are installed at the point at which gas enters the UK via pipeline, and the gas grid then undergoes conversion; which is actually minor because only the central line pipes where gas is stored at pressure need to be made of polyethylene. Most modern line pipes already are. The residential pipe network already used 'town gas' in the 1970s, so this isn't a worry.\nNow, the cost is the next part of this that people may be interested in. This is interesting to explain; because actually the 'gas' component of a gas bill is actually only 39%; the rest is operating costs and other expenses. This means that when we add the reformers where gas is entering the country, this imposes only a minor cost on the gas bill. CO2 is then safely piped offshore; and in fact Equinor (who will be the partner supplying gas) have just received licenses to find suitable storage sites in the North Sea. They have been storing carbon like this for 22 years without problems; the plain fact is that regulations have not previously been in place to necessitate the utilisation of CCS. It is not expensive or difficult. \nSo there we have it; I think this is essentially going to be the blueprint for every other country to follow. It is perfect because once you have a gas grid using decarbonised gas, every user of that gas grid is not producing emissions, be they industrial users or residential heating. And then you have transport and shipping, which will also use this gas in fuel cells. This is going to mean a faster expansion of refueling availability in the UK. \nAnd the main advantage then is that solar and wind can be plugged in at any point on the gas grid and not have to worry about highly erratic production; it just goes into the gas grid when it is produced. \nThe cost of the project is estimated by the award-winning Northern Gas Networks to mean a 7% rise in gas bills by 2035. So its not much. I think the net positive effects of the conversion will far outweigh the cost to the consumer. And transport fuel will be substantially cheaper using hydrogen (fuel cells are 50-60% efficient rather than 25% or so for combustion engines); this goes for either on-site electrolysis at the gas station or via the gas grid. \nIt will have a profound effect on everyones lives.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "124555998", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "only the central line pipes where gas is stored at pressure need to be made of polyethylene", "effect": "which is actually minor"}, {"cause": "actually the gas component is actually only 39 %", "effect": "this is interesting to explain"}, {"cause": "once you have a gas grid using decarbonised gas every user of that gas grid is not producing emissions", "effect": "it is perfect be"}]}, {"id": "124557092", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547308962000}, "author": "Daniel21x", "author_id": "101241012", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "(Part a) \nOkay, I'm going to explain this for the casual reader who may not be au fait with some the figures.\nFirst of all yes; there are multiple methods of obtaining hydrogen; and the main ones are electrolysis (power-to-gas) and reforming of methane which is employed at very large scale today in the petrol refineries and to make ammonia for fertilizer. Somewhere between 55-60 million tonnes of hydrogen are manufactured each year via natural gas. So; taking electrolysis as a primary method; the figures are quite good, although as the cost of renewable electricity decreases so too does the cost of hydrogen; and by 2030 we should have a price for electrolysed hydrogen lower than natural gas. Already, because a lot of renewable electricity is actually curtailed (its a small percentage, but it will increase), there are a lot of opportunities to produce hydrogen at low cost. With a \u00a325/MWh cost for (off-peak) wind or solar, we have reached an approximate price parity with natural gas. If we are offsetting natural gas imports, then this value could much higher as it is of greater economic value and thus perhaps a \u00a350/MWh cost for electricity is feasible, all things considered. Because you are not incurring excessive grid fees within a congested electricity grid, this reduces overall electricity costs; although crucially; finding a practical use for the hydrogen is paramount, and in this way the conversion of industrial processes and pipelines is going to become an important factor as more renewables are built. Its complicated; suffice to say that industry or gas turbines for example need to move in concert with the availability of hydrogen so as to use the energy produced.\nI will briefly explain a few important facts and metrics. First of all, no other grid-scale storage exists; batteries are far too expensive to use for heating, for example. And the electricity grid is already quite close to capacity in many instances; limiting the energy that can be distributed by wire. So we need hydrogen, because it solves both of these problems; energy can be stored at scale (man-made salt deposits for salt-cavern storage exist almost everywhere, as well as empty gas caverns; this is what is used today); and also it can be piped at high volume. Also to note that hydrogen is far safer than natural gas or petroleum, because it disperses instantly in the air. It does not self-ignite because of this characteristic. Its easy to find information on this yourself.\nSo electrolysis is a natural fit for large amounts of intermittent renewable energy and an electricity grid that is already approaching capacity.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124555998", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "a 