{"$date": 1547304694000}, "author": "quietreason", "author_id": "14769888", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "And your hydrogen? How is that to be generated? It doesn't mysteriously materialise from thin air, you know, and nor can you mine it or pump it from wells.\nHydrogen has to be generated by any of a range of processes - from refinery, consuming petroleum and releasing lots of CO2 etc into the atmosphere, to electrolysis, requiring copious supplies of electricity.\nThe electrolysis route, splitting the fiercely-bound water molecules, is energetically demanding and you get less energy out (as hydrogen and oxygen) than you pump in, so we'd need an excellent zero-carbon electricity source. Your options there would be nuclear, solar, wind and (tidal) water. But you seem to think there's some other energy source - a magic energy tree?\nThen with hydrogen you have the problems of distribution, storage and safety. All can solved, but involve very low temperatures and high pressures, and dealing with an odourless, volatile, invisible gas which will ignite explosively at almost any concentration in air.\nThen you burn the H2 in an engine? That has a rather low efficiency. Or you react it a bit more efficiently with air in fuel cells - another version of the battery (electrochemical) technology which it seems you reject.\nBetter solutions to our problems of energy generation and consumption exist. First, we need to grow up enough to contemplate radical change, such as reducing pointless consumption. Does 80kg of humanity really need to travel in a 1500kg box on wheels or could we reduce that inert mass by a factor of 10, or even 100 (to 150 or 15kg)? Do we need to able to travel at 120km/hr when we'd arrive almost as soon for a much lower energy consumption at 90? Do we need to heat the homes and workplaces to 20C when an extra layer of clothing would make 16C comfortable? Do we really need to fly to exotic places twice a year for self gratification. Is planned obsolescence such a great idea? In short, couldn't we do more and do better for half, or far less, of our present carbon footprint?\nI think the problems for society relate to a collective resistance to change, individual selfish greed and a shockingly poor general understanding of science. Time to wake up and smell the coffee.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "124554954", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124555575", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547303248000}, "author": "GoldenAppleCorps", "author_id": "17327071", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Why is the Guardian deprioritising AGW? There have been several developments in the science that are very significant, but got no mention in Guardian.", "recommendation_count": "14", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124555518", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547303012000}, "author": "GoldenAppleCorps", "author_id": "17327071", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I am a scientist. The stratosphere is cooling while the troposphere is warming. Paranoia is not a good way to determine what\u2019s real. The physics cannot be fudged, which is why the vast wealth of the fossil fuel lobby has failed to refute AGW. But you seem to think that science is controlled by a huge conspiracy orchestrated by retailers?? This is tin foil hattery. How many people are involved in this conspiracy to stimulate retail sales? It must be a lot.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "124549496", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124555161", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547301721000}, "author": "MoonlightTiger", "author_id": "17776092", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "But we should try too protect indigenous people along with tropical forests they call home. If we fail than there is not much hope for us. \n\u201cWithout the world\u2019s biggest tropical forest, there is no way to control global warming. If Bolsonaro\u2019s messianic capitalism is not stoppe