umidities, rain- or snow-falls, sea levels, and other highly variable phenomena very gradually (by our individual clocks) but inexorably change in one direction - over time scales of decades and longer - and are not returning to where they stood a mere 20 or 50 years before. Those transient local variations impress us because we see swings in a few hours which immediately affect what we feel and how we dress, but they are the mere froth on the cup of coffee, the waves at the seaside.\nIt is that slow but monotonous, never reversing trend in temperatures, which many of us barely see. It drives the melting of the world's glaciers, widens the hotter areas no longer fit for habitation and agriculture, extends periods of drought, intensifies storms, moves species towards the poles and accelerates the seemingly tiny, but one-way, trend in sea level rise. It also, because the thernal equilibrium between seawater and the massive icesheet margins of Antarctica (and Greenland) is so intensely sensitive to small variations in salinity and temperature, not only drives the dissolution if that ice into water but increases the growing risks and rates of land-ice slippage which could (and eventually will) bring sudden marked surges in global sea levels for which we are entirely unprepared.\nI hope I've given you some better insight into the overall picture, in which our passing local weather tells us almost nothing about where climate is heading?", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "124551871", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "we see swings in a few hours which immediately affect what we feel and how we dress", "effect": "those transient local variations impress us but they are the mere froth on the cup of coffee"}, {"cause": "the thernal equilibrium between seawater and the massive icesheet margins of antarctica is so intensely sensitive to small variations in salinity and temperature", "effect": "it also not only drives the dissolution if that ice into water but increase