ths will be milled for construction or fencing, while thinner sections go for biomass pellets or chipboard.\nThe Cumbrian naturalist Derek Ratcliffe likened a clear-felled plantation to a battlefield, and this is what awaits me round the corner. I pass a forester\u2019s caravan with a satellite dish and a sign warning me that I am on CCTV, and reach the summit. What I remember as a patch of open tussocks fringed with spruce (a favourite viewpoint) is now a quarry, the hill gouged out to remove the shale that surfaces the tracks. Otherwise there is nothing but a flattened mess of brash, with the occasional dead tree left standing, like the survivor of a wildfire.\nThen I hear a familiar sound. Through the still morning air comes the rising and falling chinking and clinking of a flock of crossbills in flight. They land in the bare branches of a dead tree and begin preening, their bodies silhouetted like miniature parrots against the grey sky.", "keyword_urls": ["https://www.theguardian.com/uk/scotland", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-change", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/birds", "https://www.theguardian.com/world/animals", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/wildlife", "https://www.theguardian.com/tone/features"], "share_count": "0", "description": "Wolfhopelee, Scottish Borders: What I remember as a patch of open tussocks fringed with spruce is now a quarry", "date_published": {"$date": 1547443828000}, "date_modified": {"$date": 1547809098000}, "authors": ["Tom Allan"], "article_section": "Environment", "article_tags": ["Trees and forests", "Environment", "Scotland", "Climate change", "Birds", "Animals", "UK news", "Wildlife"], "og_fields": {"og:url": "http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/jan/14/country-diary-the-spruces-time-is-up", "og:description": "Wolfhopelee, Scottish Borders: What I remember as a patch of open tussocks fringed with spruce is now a quarry", "og:image": "https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/08dd74abf49c450818e