ent research is posing interesting questions about how much effect more trees actually do have.\nHow much can forests fight climate change?\nThis is not denying the many benefits of more trees and in particular the importance of natural habitats and more liveable urban environments. But once again the critical importance of GHG emmissions in energy is underlined. If that's not fixed, everything else (including trees) cannot come anywhere near compensating.", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124872537", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547953264000}, "author": "gidrys", "author_id": "14911053", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It is indeed good to plant a tree; but that is only the start. Plants grasses and herbs and shrubs in the same vicinity, encourage mulch, try to bring the soil back to life, because chances are if you\u2019re planting in urban or former industrial-agricultural areas the soil has been killed off, all lifeforms from invertebrates to fungi are absent; the soil needs to be organic.The more diversity in flora that one can reintroduce \u2013 species wise and variety in age - the wider the range in diversity of fauna; get the bottom-end of the food-chain in place (bugs, skinks, etc) and other species will return.And it just need not be trees that are planted, for in some locations they are ill-suited; bushes and small trees make suitable alternatives.Whilst the article extols the virtues of \u2018native\u2019 trees, this comes with a few conditions dependent upon region. Some native trees constitute weeds when planted in foreign eco-systems; a well-known example being Cootamundra wattle (Acacia baileyana), a native from the Wagga wagga region, but weed from the Blue Mountains to the Otways. The preference therefore is to seek out indigenous plants; ie plants native to your specific bioregion, for not only are they well-suited to specific areas, they are very often extremely cheap or even free from community nurseries.Furthermore, according to the California Air Resources Board, a dollar spent on capturing methane from dumps, improving car gas mileage, or planting trees cuts five times as much greenhouse gas as a dollar spent on renewables. Research from Oxford Uni notes that trees help the atmosphere no matter what, they\u2019re comparatively low-cost, and they carry little additional risk. Each year, the Earth\u2019s trees suck more than a hundred billion tons of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere. Consequently, the more of us the more trees the planets needs. It is time town-planners (sic) rejected the endless urban sprawl based upon the destruction of ecosystems and included compact design with an abundance of flora.So, whilst it is indeed good to plant a tree. It is best to not destroy them in the first place, because when that happens that is only the start of a chain-reaction of consequences that are far from good..two great videos on the complexity of forests & the soil:https://www.ted.com/talks/suzanne_simard_how_trees_talk_to_each_other/discussion?utm_campaign=ios-share&utm_medium=social&source=email&utm_source=emailhttps://www.ted.com/talks/paul_stamets_on_6_ways_mushrooms_can_save_the_world?language=en https://weedsbluemountains.org.au/weeds/cootamundra-wattle/http://www.motherjones.com/environment/2018/01/can-this-colorado-city-really-afford-100-percent-clean-energy/ https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/02/the-best-technology-for-fighting-climate-change-trees/385304/https://grist.org/article/the-last-ditch-effort-to-save-the-worlds-forests-from-climate-change/", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "chances are if you \u2019re planting in urban or former industrial agricultural areas killed all lifeforms from invertebrates to fungi are absent", "effect": "try to bring the soil back to life"}, {"cause": "when that happens that is only the start of a chain reaction", "effect": "it is best to not destroy them in the fir