d by ground instruments is probably lower than the various SAT datasets are showing at present.\nHere's a recent peer-reviewed paper on the subject. The first sentence of the abstract is: \nBQSTART\nMost climatological datasets are beset with urban temperature influences that distort long-term trends.\nBQEND\nHere's\nanother (older) paper showing that UHI varies with population, therefore any station in an area experiencing population growth should experience an increase in surface temperature regardless of climate trends.\nHere's another paper showing the same thing but with high resolution satellite data.\nHere's another paper which hypothesizes that part of the temperature increase from increasing urbanization is the blocking of ground level winds by skyscraper construction.\nThe body of scientific research that demonstrates an UHI effect on ground temperature is extensive. It's unfortunate the collators of global surface temperature have chosen not to include the UHI effect in their myriad of adjustments to raw thermometer data. I think at one point the US dataset was being corrected for UHI effect, but since the other countries were not, they abandoned that approoach.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124868649", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124869895", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547938634000}, "author": "antset", "author_id": "13935202", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Developers remove trees that they are not supposed to for their own greedy needs.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124857434", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124869160", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547935633000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I once saw a Marri or Corymbia calophylla in south-west Western Australia drop a large branch on a cold day after heavy rain. However the dropping of large branches is restricted to only a few species. Where I live in Brisbane, 