ent. These trees can reach effective heights in one growing season. I have found that you can produce a very cool semi-temperate growing area on the sheltered side of a 50 metre wide tree belt with strong prevailing drying winds from the North East.\nIt is interesting that very little practical research seems to have been done on tropical wide area cooling effects of tree planting. Some studies such as \u2018Cooling Effects and Humidification Potentials in Relation to Stomatal Features in Some Shade Plants, Abdulrahaman, A. A. et al., International Journal of Applied Science and Technology Vol. 3 No. 8; December 2013\u2019 seem to be raise more questions about variety selection and the wider implications of stomata vapour loss as a mechanism to be relied on for cooling. Abdulrahaman and his colleagues concluded that \u2018Based on the canopy characteristics and stomatal features possessed by each of these shade plants as well as their rate of transpiration, species such as T. catappa, A. indica, A. lebbeck, F. trichopoda, L. cyanenscens, D. oliveri, and A. auriculiformis are the most preferable shade plant.\u2019 It seems to me that one needs to look at the effect of long-term transpiration on the area water balance as well. \nCertainly, I find that tree behaviour in response to arid conditions suggests that one may want to look for trees that actually have mechanisms for collecting and storing excess water that can be made available for transpiration during droughts. That is why I have found moringa\u2019s trunk and root storage mechanism to allow much greater heat exchanging from its multitude of small leaves when exposed to hot winds. Neem trees on the other hand offer denser shade and strong resistance to arid conditions. We can also reduce excessively drying wind speeds with other high plantings such as bambusa gigantica so that heat exchanging trees can have a longer time before they experience too much water loss and lose their ability to transpire effectively. \nIt is certainly an area where individuals can do a lot of useful work to help themselves. \nWe need a great deal more tree planting all over the tropics but individuals can effect great changes in cooling their living conditions by local planting. Keep up the good work!", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124848291", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124849365", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547877142000}, "author": "sierrasierra", "author_id": "15827133", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Really? Maybe if the council executive staffers did not pay themselves so much, there would be enough for 'public' amenities (e.g., restrooms, information displays, public telephones, rain shelters, drinking fountains, etc.) functioning kiosks on train platforms with cafe's etc. If you happen to be librarian working for a council, you earn at minimum $70K.\nRates (property taxes) have certainly risen with alarming regularity, that's what rates are meant to be used for, infrastructure and services! Because I am a property owner, I also pay \u2018fees\u2019 for parks and gardens, however Parks Victoria are now slugging you an entry fee to your local park!\nAll we seem to get are a few fields for cricket and football, a plethora of tennis courts and maybe a few BBQ's, some have a TAB attached to them; others in the same area may have a clubroom attached, more so if it\u2019s soccer club.\nOn the other hand, go to Yarra Bend and it\u2019s a different story. The Maribyrnong River runs through our local park right thru to Organ Pipes National Park, and they are worlds apart in terms of recreation, amenities and upkeep.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124848670", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124848796", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547866868000}, "author": "moveonover", "author_id": "12917821", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "In other news Kelly O'dire to quit politics at the next election.", "recommendation_cou