o and increased Carbon sequestration lead to lower atmospheric CO2, typically a drop from around 280 ppm to around 200 ppm, reducing the Earth's greenhouse effect and causing global cooling.\nThe demise of the last ice age or glacial period which occurred between 19,000 and 9,000 years ago was initiated by a peak in Northern Hemisphere high latitude summer insolation which caused a meltwater pulse into the North Atlantic from the North American and Eurasian continental glacial ice sheets. This stopped the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation, switching off the deep water currents that cool the Southern Ocean, resulting in oxidation of carbon rich oceanic oozes, causing an increase in atmospheric CO2 from 200 ppm to 280 ppm over the next 10,000 years and consequent global warming which caused the bulk of the melting and retreat of the vast glacial ice sheets which covered the high latitudes of North America and Eurasia.\nGlobal warming due to an increase in atmospheric CO2 ended the ice ages or glacial periods after orbital and axial motions initiated the process.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124931124", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "a steady decline in the insolation that occurs due to the angle at which sunlight strikes in summer at high latitudes in the northern hemisphere"}, {"cause": "the angle at which sunlight strikes in summer at high latitudes in the northern hemisphere", "effect": "that occurs"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "widespread glaciation"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "global cooling"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "lower atmospheric co2 typically a drop from around 280 ppm to around 200 ppm"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "a meltwater pulse"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "the bulk of the melting and retreat of the vast glacial ice sheets which covered the high latitudes of north america and eurasia"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "oxidation of carbon rich oceanic oozes"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "an increase 