a kind of fatal apathy: this is the way it's all set up now, they'll lose money, and all the rest of the business-as-usual litany.\nAll of that makes the transition to renewables - including, as Nicholas Stern has pointed out, hundreds of thousands of new jobs in innovation and industry - much more difficult than it should be. Governmental and industrial unwillingness and corruption also mean that societies don't have the subsidies they need to afford installing top-notch solar panels, re-engineering their homes for energy efficiency, or make other changes necessary to radically whittle emissions down. \nDuring WWII, people made the changes necessary (blackout windows, backyard shelters, stockpiling) to survive, and the government conducted a vast public-information campaign to ensure it. Faced with this enemy - us - too many want to pass the buck and too few are are unwilling to take governments to task over the needed large-scale shift. The world has made energy transitions before, although always to harmful sources. It's shocking, yet predictable - given the prevalence of those dual engines, greed and fear - that we cannot yet collectively seem to transition to benign ones.", "recommendation_count": "8", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124939895", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548096729000}, "author": "glacier", "author_id": "4706143", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It is extremely good - but only for those that are interested in proxies and less interested in forcings.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124935443", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124938827", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548094976000}, "author": "funyon", "author_id": "15956952", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Being the Change: Live Well and Spark a Climate Revolution by NASA climate scientist Peter Kalmus. In addition to a clear explanation of the science, it talks about what one person can actually do.", "recommendation_count": "1", "