: "4", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124982101", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548192204000}, "author": "SeaMonster3000", "author_id": "13262164", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It does consider all those things... and them attempts to express them in economic units.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124951252", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124989059", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548228611000}, "author": "aussiecyms", "author_id": "15962138", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Thank you so much ... I look forward to a good read.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124967083", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124988256", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548222946000}, "author": "Matt Quinn", "author_id": "16294933", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Cheers Otpus1. Total heartfelt agreement. The momentum of \"the system\" probably will not be stopped, since we're already half-way down the cliff, telling ourselves the vertigo is just performance anxiety over [insert anxiety here].\nSo I don't think change can happen at the speed of light, only communication. After that, at least we've informed ourselves a) What the real situation is and why, and b) What are our collective options? \nMost people think they understand the basics of Capitalism, Socialism and Communism, and that's all there is. While perhaps we will choose between variants of these \"known\" economic configurations, we would be shortchanging ourselves by not investigating a 4th way.\nIt was developed as a \"Middle Path\" between Capitalism(Full private ownership of value-creation) and textbook Socialism(Full public ownership of value-creation). Called \"Economic Democracy\", it has been hailed as the ultimate reconciliation between individualism, collectivism, and environmentalism by no less than Albert Einstein, Winston Churchill, Leo Tolstoy, and Aldous Huxley.\nIt is described in a free online book, Henry Georges Progress and Poverty, which built upon Adam Smiths 1776 Wealth of Nations to try to explain the failures of Classical Economics which Smith had so lamented: Industrial and Commercial recession, and the problem of persistent poverty amidst almost unimaginable technical progress. The introduction could have been written in 2019:\nBQSTART\nYet we must now face facts we cannot mistake. All over the world, we hear complaints of industrial depression: labor condemned to involuntary idleness; capital going to waste; fear and hardship haunting workers. All this dull, deadening pain, this keen, maddening anguish, is summed up in the familiar phrase \"hard times.\" ~ Henry George, San Francisco 1879\nBQEND\nIn a nutshell, by scrambling the definitions of Land(aka nature), Wealth(what you want/need) and Money(sharing/trading mechanism) by magically pronouncing them all to be interchangeable forms of Capital(wealth reserved to make more wealth), the linkage between the Earth and real value(usable wealth) is lost.\nCapitalism says Land equals Wealth equalsMoney equals Capital, which means pretty much whatever whoever controls the Myrmidons of the rent-takers wants it to mean.\nThat is of course, until production cannot underwrite the enormous rents, brutally extracted at whatever the market will bear. Then the economy crashes, and the monopoly game starts again on a smaller board.\nEconomic Democracy rights this obfuscation, by assigning the correct relationship as:Land causes Wealth causes Money with _repeated_ application of Labor, true Capital and Trade.\nNominal owners of natural opportunities should pay for civilization, not those who do the work of building and maintaining it. Economic Democracy suggests a simple market-based mechanism to get the most out of the least land, while the benefits of land ownership accrue to everyone, not just inheritors. Everyone has incentive to make sure land doesn't degrade, and the power to enforce those desires.\nIf you're interested in further investigation, especially in why no one seems to know about this, or pretends they do and insists it is old hat even though they can't explain why, Here are a few rabbit holes I found fascinating. I've also written a lot in these comments if you have absolutely nothing else better to do. Questions and thoughts most welcome.\n~ How Land Barons, Industrialists and Bankers Corrupted Economics, Dierdre Kent 2016.The Corruption - detailsWhat Money is: Seven Deadly Innocent Frauds of Economic Policy, Mosler 2010 P1.What Wealth is: Progress and Poverty, Henry George 1879, esp intro, ch3, 17.How we got to Now: The Corruption of Economics, Mason Gaffney 1994 p 29-44. Excellent Prologue by Fred Harrison: Who's Afraid of Henry George?\nFor sincere and willing truth-seekers, this short list cannot fail to deeply reward even a cursory treatment. Namaste.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124987625", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "wealth", "effect": "money"}, {"cause": "land", "effect": null}]}, {"id": "124981558", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548190539000}, "author": "Mshawdjflex", "author_id": "12167977", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I work in the area of greenhouse reduction and sustainable building design and I remember the disappointment I felt when Australia's relatively week carbon price was introduced. This was particularly obvious when viewed through the lens of my own lifestyle. Pricing in environmental externalities would never cause me to stop using my landlord's electric storage domestic hot water unit, it wouldn't quickly decarbonise Victoria's high carbon brown coal electricity generators, nor would it encourage my landlord to install photovoltaic panels on the roof of his investment property for my benefit. The carbon price would also not encourage me to abandon my petrol vehicle for my 20 minute commute to and from work. The changes necessary would have been a) far better public transport services for journeys not sta