parrow's opposition to cap and trade schemes is completely irrational and even dangerous as the alternative he offers is economically inefficient and authoritarian.\nCap and trade schemes can be and will be gamed. However the purpose of lawmakers and regulators is to minimise gaming. Cap and trade schemes work, which is why they have been so vehemently opposed by conservatives and industry groups.\nSparrow is right that, without compensation, they are inherently regressive. However, shutting down power stations by government edict has the same regressive effect on prices and will be equally unpopular if there is no compensation. The solution is to arrange compensation through the social welfare and/or tax system.\nCap and trade is the way to go because it encourages innovative, lowest cost solutions to a shared program. Top down solutions are limited by the imaginations of a handful of politicians and their advisors.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "124949501", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it encourages innovative solutions to a shared program", "effect": "to go"}]}, {"id": "124979983", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548185172000}, "author": "rockyrex", "author_id": "2923581", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Exactly.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124952031", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124987625", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548217710000}, "author": "optus1", "author_id": "12048513", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Matt Quinn: Thanks for your reply.  I agree with you that \"it's not enough to say greed\". It's not......I think that way back when, it all started out with good and right intentions, the vision and hope of a better world for more people. Plus it started out with a whole lot of ignorance - i.e. lack of knowledge and understanding. Then at some point, the ignorance became less and less.\nHowever, even though we were no longer ignorant, we kept up all the \"business as usual\