 Magpies stopped by. A few walked on the floor around my legs. Some sat on the tables behind me. And one very friendly Magpie came right up close and sat on the table beside me.They chirped and sang and chatted loudly to each other. Up and down with their sing-song sounds which to my ear, sounded like the sweetest chorus. Their chorus was so good and so clear that I wished I'd had a device with me to record them.\nThe reason I thought of recording them was because I wondered how much longer they'd be around for me or anyone to see and hear them up close, personal and first-hand. I wondered how long it would be before the only place I'd see them would be in some select enclosure or zoo or via some documentary or digital vision. And I wondered how long it would be before the only way I could hear their sounds would be on a CD or some App or similar. I wondered how much longer the water would still be running in the river and how much longer the ducks would still be alive and able to fly there in perfect formation.\nI prefer to use the yardstick of the Civil Law Courts i.e The BALANCE of PROBABILITIES.So I sat there and thought - on the balance of probabilities?  Still here in 5 years? Probably - but not confident enough to punt the house and the dog on it......10 years? Maybe - but probably nowhere near their current numbers and not anywhere near their current conditions.15 years?  Doubtful. Unlikely. Don't like their chances at all. Wouldn't even punt my breakfast coffee on it.20 years? Very highly probably...dead in the water. Literally. River stale or run dry. Just a memory. No more ducks. No more Magpies. What trees there are - near lifeless.\nBeyond that? By the time one gets to \"beyond that\" it's all already HISTORY....", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "i wondered how much longer they 'd be around for me or anyone to see and hear them up close hand", "effect": "the reason i thought of recording them was"}]}, {"id": "124986615", "ti