ulture, cities and civilization.\nFor a very long time now we've dialed in a lot of change. The paper below, published recently, raises an interesting question regarding adaptation to long-term climate change.\nFrom the abstract:\nBQSTART\nAdaptation is the process of adjusting to climate change in order to moderate harm or exploit beneficial opportunities associated with it. Most adaptation strategies are designed to adjust to a new climate state. However, despite our best efforts to curtail greenhouse gas emissions, climate is likely to continue changing far into the future.\nBQEND\nThe paper uses the example of sea level rise, currently around 4.4mm per year, to show one example of long-term, continuous change in climate.\nBQSTART\nOver the next 1000 years, sea-level is projected to rise at an average rate of 3.44 cm yr\u22121, if all available fossil fuel resources are combusted and the CO2 released to the atmosphere.\nBQEND\nWhere would we rebuild our coastal cities, naval facilities and sea ports? There\u2019d be no stable shoreline in any time scale of interest to humans.\nhttp://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.1088/1748-9326/11/10/104007/meta", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124702545", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547621321000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Meanwhile there's 5,000 comments often on the Kardashians or some football player. As Frank Zappa once said, the world's most plentiful ingredient is stupidity.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "124700565", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124700565", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547606700000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Whatever, not much interest in most of our large cities going under water sooner than expected.\nHow\u2019s the recent football scores? Or Brexit?", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_re