 have mixed the clay in with the improved soil and general composting keeps on top of things by adding soil volume each year.\nOne benefit has been our council has adopted strict recycling targets which means you HAVE to compost because the bins are just far too small to just recycle. A rabbit turns a large amount of green waste into ready to use compost and he takes up much less space than a recycling/compost bin and that is important in my small garden and it cuts down on flies and associated problems with composting which are also problematic in smaller gardens.\nMy rabbit (and chickens when I kept them) are free range, raised beds protect the crops I really care about. Chickens destroy everything but I\u2019ve found rabbits tend to calm down over time and don\u2019t destroy everything- I grow kale just for the rabbit, the rabbit loves dandelions so they are absent from the garden, and we agree to share things like sorrel and similar salad crops.\nAnd of course a rabbit is a cheap pet. He also hates cats so keeps our garden free from cats which encourages the birds. It is funny to watch the birds group around the rabbit in the garden for protection while they fill up on insects. \nI\u2019m not self sufficient in any way, I don\u2019t have the space or inclination, in fact \u2018no dig\u2019 suits my rather lazy nature.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "124635701", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "red"}, {"cause": "the bins are just far too small to just recycle", "effect": "which means you have to compost"}]}, {"id": "124641766", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547530847000}, "author": "dianab", "author_id": "3093009", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Yes, it's probably going to be a slug fest this year - might give my neighbour's fav method a go- get yourself 20 odd slugs from a couple of different sites (to raise chances of some being infected with nematodes, I believe)-put them in covered bucket to drown- leave the 