madic, or we were less so) we enriched the soil in the short term, partly by natural composting and manure, partly by bringing soil nutrients into play over time.\nLater we collectivise and protect our land against other groups, and that reinforces \u2018digging\u2019, and that pressure on land just increases over time.\nFast forward to today and things are different and you could adopt no dig as the land has long been cleared and parcelled out. Over a decade ago my back garden soil was dead and contaminated, dead from years of being used to grow crops (the last pig was shot on the property in 1928) and dead because a steel works had been built a few miles away and over the years it had contaminated the soil. I dug away a good 30 cm of soil and disposed of it, and then over time rebuilt the soil level by keeping chickens, rabbits, and growing certain crops- the land had become overgrown so there was a lot of tree/shrub wood that was mulched and added and that takes years to give up its nutrients. After about 12 years the soil was fine (it was tested) and the soil height had increased. Now I use no dig, mainly using raised beds- the soil is very productive. I still have one rabbit at the moment (hence raised beds) and he does a good job of enriching the soil as he will eat kitchen scraps- I don\u2019t give him meat although he happily eats a leftover Sunday dinner given half the chance. Rabbits are great soil improvers, as their manure isn\u2019t \u2018hot\u2019 unlike chickens (although they give you eggs).", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "124632409", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "a steel works had been built a few miles away and over the years it had contaminated the soil", "effect": "the last pig was shot on the property in 1928 and dead"}]}, {"id": "124634755", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547501438000}, "author": "xwookey", "author_id": "4307215", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It takes time to change infrastructure. Because