ay, is being superseded by mulching: https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/oct/21/stop-digging-it-is-bad-for-your-soil-and-you-james-wong Worms do the work of aeration. Unless your soils are compacted massively, the mulch method works wonderfully and the worms do the 'digging'. Alys Fowler is just one of the seasoned gardeners to adopt this approach.", "recommendation_count": "10", "in_reply_to": "124625655", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124632409", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547495847000}, "author": "AnitaIslington", "author_id": "15225337", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "If digging was bad, and mulching better, people would have stopped digging years ago, surely? https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/oct/21/stop-digging-it-is-bad-for-your-soil-and-you-james-wong", "recommendation_count": "0", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124628762", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547486958000}, "author": "LaviniaWhateley", "author_id": "17915835", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "And fashion...oh gods the fashion...", "recommendation_count": "10", "in_reply_to": "124618925", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124628631", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547486798000}, "author": "Armini", "author_id": "10023586", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Carbon monoxide oxidizes quite quickly in the atmosphere. Hydrocarbons tend not to have significant uptake by plants, but do inhibit germination and growth. What is produced should not be significantly affected. Soot effects depend heavily on composition, but most of those carbons are not particularly harmful for plants - far more hazardous to the gardener than the garden.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "124624168", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124628196", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547486244000}, "author": "1000100101", "author_id": "100795284", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "To Bee or Not to Bee?", "recommenda