s an enormous amount of carbon dioxide dissolved in it and the amount dissolved depends on the temperature just as much as the fizz in a bottle of Coke. When it warms some carbon dioxide out-gasses, it goes flat. The rises and falls in atmospheric carbon dioxide FOLLOW the rises and falls in ocean temperature.\"\nNo they don't. From 19,000 to 9,000 years ago the rise in global ocean temperatures followed the rise in atmospheric carbon dioxide.\nAt 33 degrees C I don't have much experience with Coke, but the tonic in my G&T follows the same principle. However even if I return the tonic water to the fridge but leave its lid off, it still goes flat. Pressure change over time plays a greater role in determining whether your fizzy drink will go flat. Temperature largely affects the rate at which this happens. When you remove your fizzy drink from the fridge, and unscrew the cap, it fizzes immediately, not due to the temperature change of the bottles contents - there has not been sufficient time for that, even at 33 degrees C - but due to the sudden pressure decrease.\nSimilarly in the ocean, while the ability of sea water to dissolve CO2 decrease with temperature, increasing atmospheric CO2 concentration and partial pressure is causing more CO2 to dissolve in the oceans reducing their pH. While some of this CO2 may come from the oceans, most of the net increase comes from the known combustion of fossil fuels.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124751993", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the temperature change of the bottles contents", "effect": "when you remove your fizzy drink from the fridge it fizzes immediately there has not been sufficient time for that"}, {"cause": "the sudden pressure decrease", "effect": "even at 33 degrees c but"}, {"cause": "the ability of sea water to dissolve co2 decrease with temperature increasing atmospheric co2 concentration and partial pressure", "effect": "more co2 to dissolve in the oceans reducing their"}]}, {"id": "124809264", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547781134000}, "author": "IanGeorge", "author_id": "12887728", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I'm sorry. I only look at the data and it doesn't entirely bear out what you seem to think is happening. Isn't that what one is supposed to do?", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124807983", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124809109", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547780237000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"Satellite measurement, untampered and continuous, is available and shows no warming in 20 years.\"\nYou need around 30 years of data to measure climate temperature. 20 years of data is not enough.\nSatellites measure the temperature of the upper troposphere high above where humans live. Satellite data requires considerable adjustment (tampering) before it provides you with a measure of the temperature of the upper troposphere.\n\"Photographic evidence shows no significant rise in mean ocean surface levels in places known to be geologically stable - the land is neither sinking nor rising.\"\nMean ocean surface levels are measured using radar based satellites not by photographic means. Such satellite based measures are not affected by tectonism or geological instability. Global sea level rose between 20 cm between 1884 and 2014, an average rate of about 1.8 mm per year. By the later half of the 20th century that rate had increased to 3 mm per year.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124751993", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124808794", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547778072000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"3. Temperature data is being falsified and always in the direction of increase. Closed data sources are being guessed at. Coverage is being diminished particularly in sites in the former Soviet Union and most of the planet has no data being measured at all. Existent measures of temperature data which used to be in normal environments are now in carparks or airports subject to local urban temperature increase. Published IPCC graphs past and present illustrate this to be true but the emails were icing on the cake.\" On land global temperature data is based on measurements made by meteorological organisations such as the Australian Bureau of Meteorology. In determining which sites more accurately reflect regional as distinct from local and urban climate temperature meteorologists take into account such factors as the urban heat island affect, changes in shading and wind tunneling from buildings as well as changes in vegetation in both urban, suburban and agricultural areas. They don't falsify data but remove sites or adjust data from sites to remove these cooling and biases in the measure of the regional climate temperature. Sites have removed or adjustments made which result in the cooling of the data, not always in a increase in the climate temperature shown by the data. Removal of a site or adjustment of the data from a site to remove the bias produced by an urban heat island will result in decrease in the temperatures shown by the data.\nThese data sources are not guessed at, nor are they closed but can be accessed on line. Adjustments are made and sites abandoned, in the determination of regional climate temperature, for objective reasons reflecting the factors discussed in the preceding paragraph. Ships and buoys measure ocean temperatures while sparsely populated countries such as Australia have a good coverage of meteorological stations. Any shortfall in central Asia would reflect the policies of the current Russian and US administrations. Removal of urban heat island bias from data in the 90s and earlier produced cooling of that data whereas recent increases in climate temperature data reflect global climate trends. You can't hide from reality by disingenuously accusing the messenger of falsification or misinterpreting casually written stolen private emails.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "124751993", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "which", "effect": "the cooling of the data"}, {"cause": "removal of a site or adjustment of the data from a site to remove the bias produced by an urban heat island", "effect": "decrease in the temperatures shown by the data"}]}, {"id": "124808338", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547775301000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"2. Enormous amounts of work have been done in numerous disciplines in my lifetime. Collectively it has provided us with very good ideas of what has happened through history going back millions of years. The carbon cycle is not one of the parameters having any significant causal role in determining the climate.\"\nYour last sentence is wrong. The carbon cycle was the major factor in causing the global warming which led to the end of the last glacial period or \"ice age\" over the 10,000 years of deglaciation between 19,000 and 9,000 years ago. The carbon cycle was also the cause of the early mid-Pliocene warming around 5 million years ago and the Palaeocene Eocene thermal maximum 55.5 million years ago.\n\"The current state of knowledge is that a significant number of periodic variables in the solar system and the sun itself drive the planet's climate.\"\nThe sun's energy output as a star has been increasing very slowly through the 4.543 billion years of the Earth's existence. This rate of increase is far to slow to have any noticeable impact on the Earth's climate in times spans of a couple of million to a couple of centuries over which which we have observed recent and Pleistocene climate change.\nPeriodic changes in the Earth's axial tilt, eccentricity of rotation and the point in the planets orbit where it is closest to the sun cause cycles in Northern Hemisphere high latitude summer insolation (NHHLSI) over periods of 10,000 to 100,000 years. A peak in NHHLSI 19,000 years ago produced some melting of the North American and north Eurasian glacial continental ice sheets which at that time extended as far south as the regions of Yosemite, Chicago, New York, London, Milan and Belgrade.\nThis produced a large meltwater pulse in the North Atlantic shutting the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC) which cools the Southern Ocean, which led to oxidation of oceanic oozes in the Southern Ocean increasing atmospheric CO2 resulting in global greenhouse warming over the next 10,000 years causing the Northern Hemisphere continental glacial ice sheets to retreat to their current levels.\nAtmospheric CO2 reached 280 ppm 8,000 years ago on the shoulder of that NHHLSI peak. NHHLSI has declined slowly since then and will continue to do so for the next 50,000 years, at which time, if atmospheric CO2 had remained at the usual interglacial level of around 280 ppm, the glacial period or \"ice age\" would have started. If atmospheric CO2 is still at, near or above current levels of 410 ppm that next glacial period will not occur. Our most productive agricultural soils are in the Northern Hemisphere associated with glacial sediments produced by the glacial / deglacial cycle.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124751993", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "the global warming which led to the end of the last glacial period or age"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "the end of the last glacial period or age"}, {"cause": "periodic changes in the earth 's axial tilt eccentricity of rotation and the point in the planets orbit where it is closest to the sun", "effect": null}, {"cause": null, "effect": "global greenhouse warming"}, {"cause": "which", "effect": "oxidation of oceanic oozes in the southern ocean"}]}, {"id": "124807983", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547773443000}, "author": "Gregory Shearman", "author_id": "14899696", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text