ur precious beach. As one long-term mahogany-brown resident declared, they stood out like a nude in a gumboot - I have never forgotten that vivid expression. The fact that renowned jazz pianist, Winifred Atwell, lived in Flight Deck was cause for awe by some but not enough to stop the objections to more high-rise development. For most of the year I was locked up in boarding school and could not get to sleep for ages there because I missed the sound of the waves at home. As soon as I was home for the holidays, I would run from Long Reef, around its magical rock pools and cliffs which were treasure troves of amazing fossils, long since eroded by waves of school excursions. Then around the 9-hole golf course where we would sell golf balls we had found in the scrub and sand back to the players, past the little fishing 'village' where an assortment of tinnies were stored for use by fisherfolk when they weren't fishing from the beach with their long, long rods. My Dad and I would go out before dawn in one of those tinnies, fish off the head at Long Reef, and after the tinnie was stored, we would dig a hole in the sand and cook our catch for an early dawn breakfast. Just adjacent lies The Basin with its secret cunji island where we would prise the meat out of those little sea squirts to use as bait, and explore its wondrous underwater secrets revealed in long hours of snorkelling its reef which formed the natural eponymous basin, perfectly safe for children and infants to play on its shore; around the headland to the ocean pools with their chain fence - big one for grown ups and the smaller one for the kids, where once a man became stuck in the outlet when the pool was being emptied for maintenance and the episode was the talk of the locals for weeks. Whenever I see the glossy-leaf mock laurel, I am always reminded of hedges framing the main beach against the backdrop of the Children's Hospital where kids with polio and other handicapping conditions were brought to have some time in the sun, out on the sloping lawns, many of them in their beds. Those lawns were such fun to roll down on the way to the playground with its swings which seemed to be the longest in the world to my child's eyes. How many times we would all run to the surf club to get the lifesavers to rub us down with vinegar when we were stung by bluebottles; how often did we get rides in the long wooden surf boats riding great wave sets into the shore. How often were we amazed by the beautifully crafted sand sculptures created for the competitions run by the Daily Tellie. How many memorable evenings were spent around bonfires on the beach as spin the bottle was played and first boyfriends discovered. In later years how proud we were to know we learned to ride boards alongside the giants Midge Farrelly, Nat Young, Mark Warren and their mates in the days when there was room for everyone and we Gidget girls were still very much a novelty especially if we paddled out to surf the bombora off Long Reef\u2026", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "124754022", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "i missed the sound of the waves at home", "effect": "could not get to sleep for ages there"}]}, {"id": "124758472", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1547700674000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"three studies have found evidence that the threat of higher seas is also undermining coastal property values as home buyers \u2014 particularly investors \u2014 begin the retreat to higher ground.\"\nhttps://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/sea-level-rise-is-eroding-home-value-and-owners-might-not-even-know-it/2018/08/20/ff63fa8c-a0d5-11e8-93e3-24d1703d2a7a_story.html?utm_term=.f8eba54ca57e\nBut yeah, that's with what, around 8 inches of global mean sea level rise. It will get expensive real fast.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "124758364", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "124758373", "ti