es C with a central tendency of 2.8 degrees. So this experiment did not falsify the ECS with a central tendency of 2.8 degrees C but in fact produced a result close to the central tendency. As the Earth's climate system is unlikely to have yet reached equilibrium for a 40% increase in atmospheric CO2 the slightly lower value is to be expected.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125075883", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125082318", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548420589000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"According to what epistemology does an inference, an estimate or a probability have the status of being a fact.\"\nA fact is a thing that is known or proved to be true. In science we know things to be true based on observations of which measurements are a subset - these provide the evidence that something exists and what size it is.\nAn inference is a conclusion based on evidence and reasoning. Scientific facts are based on evidence and reasoning. So scientific facts can be inferences.\nAn estimate is an approximate calculation. Calculation of Earth's ECS to CO2 based on observations and measurement produces an approximate result with a central tendency of 2.8 degrees C and a 'likely' range of 2.2 to 3.4 degrees C. That estimate is a fact.\nA probability is the extent to which something is likely to happen or be the case. The likely probability is that the ECS discussed above is between 2.2 and 3.4 degrees C with the highest likelihood occurring occurring near the central tendency of 2.8 degrees C. Probabilities things that are known and can be proved to be true based on evidence, observation and measurements and are therefore also facts.\n\"That is to say the status of the most secure form of knowledge about the natural world we have\".\nThe most secure form of knowledge about the natural world is scientific knowledge which involves conclusions based on evidence and reasoning (inferences), approximate calculations (estimates) and descriptions of the likelihood that something is likely to happen or be the case (probabilities) - all of which are facts.\nBy examining the synoptic weather data over my continent meteorologists can infer that the temperature in my city will reach 31 degrees C on a day which is partly cloudy. This is an approximate result or estimate. Depending on whether there is more or less cloud the maximum temperature may be plus or minus a degree. The probability that the maximum temperature tomorrow will be between 30 and 32 degrees is very high particularly when the blocking high is taken into consideration. \nThe real world we live in is not one of secure facts but of inferences, estimates and probabilities based on solid evidence. If you desire greater security than that, perhaps you are not made for the real world.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125075883", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125064577", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548365193000}, "author": "BuzzBloodOhio space", "author_id": "17722198", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "in the absence of any other study, it remains convincing. Or do you have one up your sleeve?\nsecondly, you have not actually expressed by its not convincing, other than you not liking hte dates 1920's to 1991 for some bizarre reason. Science was still quite advanced in the 1990's you know.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "125064443", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125064443", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548364845000}, "author": "ID2310987", "author_id": "2515806", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "That's a 1991 study with data from the 1920's til then. Checks calendar, it's now 2019. Not very convincing.", "recommendation_count": "7", "in_reply_to": "125064187", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125080174", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548416942000}, "author": "BuzzBloodOhio space", "author_id": "17722198", "schema_o