ntarctica melt - the opposite happens - it will introduce water to the ocean - but also have reduced pulling-effect on the water that already is in the ocean - so making the effect larger in the tropics and in the northern hemisphere. \nIf we get back to the effect on the moon - some places the effect of tides are measured in tens of meters - other places hardly noticable. It is all fine. But because of physics - same effects are in operation when ice melts - the stuff that cause trend on top of variability. \n(Importantly, our dear Luna and the tides also have a trend when we discuss geological time scales - just like the influence of the Sun also has a trend over long time-scales - and even more importantly - climate science takes potential reasons of climate trend so seriously that climate science still take the 18.6 year lunar cycle into account as part of reality (although not as crazy as some blogger who heard about it in 1970 still does to \"prove\" that Co2 is radiative neutral/just gas of life). \nThe issue with slow sea-level change is that all sorts of stuff happens when the high-tide moves slowly up - and by default start to interact with infrequent storm-surges. Because that is when water ends up in places it did not use to end up just a few decades ago.", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "125051023", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "lack of a tidally locked big mass in orbit", "effect": "in effect our moon stop earth from doing as our sister planet mars tilting"}, {"cause": "their gravitational effects", "effect": "they also pull sea level towards them"}, {"cause": "that", "effect": "trend on top of variability"}]}, {"id": "125064187", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548364127000}, "author": "BuzzBloodOhio space", "author_id": "17722198", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "ummm no, the science does not say Shanghai for instance will be emerged in ocean with a 3c rise in temperatures.\nCurrent rates of sea level rise are only 1m