c CO2 levels and use those somewhat more direct measures, in conjunction with our observation and measurement based knowledge of how the oceans and atmosphere interact, to produce a measure of equilibrium climate sensitivity for Earth in response to atmospheric levels of the greenhouse gas CO2.\nYou have talked about facts. What are facts? Facts are what we can observe about the world and universe around us. It's a fact that my front steps exist because I can observe and measure them. It's a fact that the temperature in my city now is 29 degrees C because I have access to a reliable measure. It's a fact that global climate temperatures have increased because we have access to reliable measures of them. It's a fact that atmospheric CO2 concentrations have increased because we have access to reliable measures of them. So why is it that the measure of equilibrium climate sensitivity with a central tendency of 2.7 degrees C for this planet in response to atmospheric CO2 concentration is not a fact to you?", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "125057532", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "i have observed them and tested their strength with my weight many times over the last 15 years", "effect": "that my front steps exist"}, {"cause": "i have observed it", "effect": "that the fungal wood rot exists"}, {"cause": "i have measured it", "effect": "i know the length of the step"}, {"cause": "i have access to a reliable measure", "effect": "that the temperature now in brisbane is 29 degrees c"}, {"cause": "i can observe and measure them", "effect": "that my front steps exist"}, {"cause": "i have access to a reliable measure", "effect": "that the temperature in my city now is 29 degrees c"}, {"cause": "we have access to reliable measures of them", "effect": "that global climate temperatures have increased"}, {"cause": "we have access to reliable measures of them", "effect": "that atmospheric co2 concentrations have increased"}]}, {"id": "125069246", "time_stamp": {"$date"