 all.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "124984086", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "125012817", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548262361000}, "author": "glacier", "author_id": "4706143", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Science is not just testing climate engineering - science invented the idea. \nClimate engineering is also tested. Most famously in China - but also on many an airport around the world (to affect fog). \nClimate engineering is also tested globally by natural events - such as explosive volcanic injection of ash into the stratosphere. They cause a time-limited period of up to 3 years of cooled global temperature. They also cause the UK to end up in a permanent state of positive NAO weather (very wet and mild and stormy) while southern Europe are fixed in drought. \nAll because of simple physics - even the first generation climate models had enough physics to explain why this happens. \nSo now you have to explain to the people in the UK that they will live permanently in the saddest weather you had in the 1990s - forever - to save the planet. Just like the Chinese stopped cloud-seeding - because it turned out that the already moisture stressed regions down-wind start to go desert on them. \nYou also must consider laws of warfare - because if Israel start to fix local rain - those located a bit further east may see it as an attack of own freshwater source. \nIn more general terms - climate science do not have good call on the regional effects and how fast they respond to CO2. So do you think it is a good idea to square the complexity by adding some radiative fix into the equations? \nIt could be a bit like pouring ice cold water into the petrol tank to help the engine from overheating. It may sound like a fantastic idea to draw ice cold water into the engine along with petrol. But some expert on car engines may advice against it. \nWe can learn this by trial and failure with engines - since we have many of them. But we have only one planet. Where do you think is the best place to engineer the radiative, conductive and convective heat?\nCarbon capture and storage is of course an engineering solution. But that makes all combustion energy instantly too expensive. So it is cheaper to just forbid it and instead transfer the generous subsidies for fossil energy to into nuclear. I like nuclear a lot - except from the direct and indirect cost. As such - the best engineering solution at present is to forbid subsidies to fossil carbon and move that generous tax generated subsidies to nuclear - while giving renewable energy that is on the brink of not needing subsidies at all some love with distributed grid understanding. \nThe trash from nuclear is after all contained until we learn a permanent solution for it. A much worse case than nuclear is that we power the planet with fossils for another century and end up in a situation with a climate crisis so bad that we are spending all the cash on fixing that rather than to care for the radioactive stockpiles we already caretake. \nBy making more nuclear waste we at least lower the much worse problem of AGW. This, of course, will increase the cost of energy a lot. Even with more cheap renewables to help out. But in the long run it is cheap. All self-contained energy is cheap. \nRemember - it is not the heat from a car engine or a coal plant that heats the world. It is the byproduct that heats the planet. As such we will embrace fusion. Because it is not the millions of degrees in the core that will stop us from heating up the planet. It is lack of emissions that does that. The problem with fusion is of course that even though the fuel is for free the cost of constructing the machine that sustain the heat and energy for so long that the output of energy is more than the input of energy is not cheap at all. \nI am go for nuclear. Because we are painted into a corner so tight that ideology lost decades ago. \nSadly, the president of USA and president of Russia and many other leaders have decided that nuclear power again is to be associated with nuclear weapon treaties as they are eager to pull out of treaties decades old. \nThat nuclear energy again is associated with weapon grade radioactivity and missiles is not helping the energy industry that has tried to detach itself from the war-games for a long time. \nIt seems like world leaders want to keep nuclear capacity as a military exclamation mark - and not as a civil safe source of energy - in a way that makes fossil energy to look good. Russia is a big player in fossil energy. USA is a big player in fossil energy. They do not want civil nuclear energy. It is still a weapon. And they do not want other nations to be allowed nuclear power plants. Better to keep them running on fossils. \nNuclear always had a hard time.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "125008412", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "they", "effect": "a time limited period of up to 3 years of cooled global temperature"}, {"cause": "they", "effect": "the uk to end up in a permanent state of positive nao weather wet while southern europe are fixed in drought"}, {"cause": "simple physics", "effect": "even the first generation climate models had enough physics to explain why this happens"}, {"cause": "it turned out that the already moisture stressed regions down start", "effect": "just like the chinese stopped cloud seeding"}, {"cause": "if israel start to fix local rain those located a bit further east may see it as an attack of own freshwater source", "effect": "you also must consider laws of warfare"}]}, {"id": "125012502", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1548261970000}, "author": "jmserrat", "author_id": "4667618", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The white Caucasian world will survive? Do not kid yourself. SOME white Caucasians will survive. The very rich, regardless of ethnicity, will survive. You and I, and our children, may not.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_repl